text=(:comment page text goes here:)%0a!!Show Hidden Files on your Mac%0aLaunch the Terminal and enter these commands exactly as shown. The first command activates the ability to see the hidden files:%0a%0a(:source lang=bash:)%0a defaults write com.apple.Finder AppleShowAllFiles TRUE%0a(:sourceend:)%0a%0aNow you must relaunch the Finder by killing it, this is how the changes take effect:%0a%0a(:source lang=bash:)%0a killall Finder%0a(:sourceend:)%0a%0aIf you want to hide hidden files again (those preceded with a .) and go back to the default Mac settings, you can just type the following:%0a%0a(:source lang=bash:)%0a defaults write com.apple.Finder AppleShowAllFiles FALSE%0a(:sourceend:)%0a%0aAgain you will need to kill the Finder so that it can relaunch for changes to take effect:%0a%0a(:source lang=bash:)%0a killall Finder%0a(:sourceend:)%0a%0aThat’s all there is to it!%0a%0a!!Show Hidden Files in a Mac Save Dialogue%0aYou can quickly show all hidden files in any Mac OS X save dialogue box by hitting Command+Shift+Period%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a>>comment%3c%3c%0aSummary:How to see dot (hidden) files in OX/X%0aParent:(Technology.)OSX%0aincludeme:[[Technology.OSX]]%0aCategories:[[!HowTos]]%0aTags: hidden files, osx, finder%0a(:tags-hide hidden files, osx, finder:)%0aSource: http://osxdaily.com/2009/02/25/show-hidden-files-in-os-x/%0a>>%3c%3c
